:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local Decision-Making as it works in the City of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with 3 layers of local government means that the different layers of council spend a lot of time commenting on each other’s plans, but little is produced in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> way of transport infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on the ground</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There is no cycling budget at WSCC, no cycling strategy and no cycling officer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and yet WSCC is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">responsible for transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but spends most of its budget on roads only allowing cycling to benefit from odd bits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of S106 monies which it has to fight for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:15.6pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here are lots of officers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">especially at county level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the left hand often does not know what the right hand is doing.  Any committees/ departments among the officers of the councils to promote sustainable tra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vel seem not to have the support of the councillors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, or their influence seems limited</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – except </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the councillors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> know</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the various planning documents they produce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contain references to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sustainable travel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but the reality is that when schemes actuall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y get to be put on lists they are schemes to promote increased capacity on junctions and cycling and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">walking is not high up on the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> agenda</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or rather non-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">existant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1) What is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Decisions about transport infrastructure hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been devolved to the County Local Committees.  They are allowed to pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gress 3 Traffic Regulation Orders a year.  They cover a large area and having such a limit put on their decisions means that a lot of time is spent on deciding which 3 schemes will be progressed.  Inevitably this means that a huge number of schemes get on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the list but never actually get done.  People are asked to provide support for their scheme and hand in petitions.  Even if you hand in a petition there is no guarantee that the scheme will go ahead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> petition for a crossing at Walnut Tree Pub in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">North </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mundham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resulted in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a £10,000 study but no crossing for the children to get to the local school on foot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The members on the County Local Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seem aware of promoting sustainable travel but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the need to “keep traffic flowing” and “increase ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pacity” are higher up the political agenda.  Cycle paths for leisure are promoted over and above schemes on busy junctions or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gyratories</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or arterials for utility cycling.  Sustainable travel does not have a proper budget but is dependent on S106 funding – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">so there is no way of getting repairs to cycle paths or new facilities progressed.  A new bridge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for pedestrians and cyclists </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was put in over the railway in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  When this was planned the councillors’ attention was brought to the fact that cargo tr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ikes and trailers would have to use this bridge.  The turns are too tight for these vehicles and a row of bollards have been put in on the road to prevent cars from parking near the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bridge but they are too close together and now cargo trikes and trailers c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">annot turn off the road</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to get to the crossing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">!</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> To change this, this will have to be put on a list to be put to the CLC meeting and it w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ill have to bid for S106 monies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  It is very unlikely that this will be prioritized over other schemes in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Selsey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chiche</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, The Bourne and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tangmere</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Road schemes are prioritized that often do not include an element for cycling.  </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Undoubtedly it is important that local bodies make decisions about what transport schemes ought to be progressed.  However if the local body i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s not made up of transport professionals, is influenced by political concerns above all, and has a huge list of projects to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from and finally is only able to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 3 a year, it is not surprising that this approach does not bring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any advantages for th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e residents.  A better model would have better funding – not just chasing S106 monies, would have clear guidelines so as to promote sustainable travel as a proper means of transport, rather than as the Cinderella of Motor transport.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no coherent s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">trategy to develop national and regional cycle routes that cross political boundaries.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Responsibility for cycling schemes has been devolved to a lower level (County Local Committees) than road schemes (County Council).  As a result, road schemes are being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">put forward without a cycling element - sometimes resulting in worse cycling infrastructure.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">transport boards) have the capacity to assess, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">prioritise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The structure we have at the moment means that a lot of plans are produced but local transport schemes for cycli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng are not being delivered.  There is no mechanism to ensure that what </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> District Council says is necessary to promote sustainable travel is carried out. There have been cuts to funding to local government, changes of staff, and there is no dedica</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ted cycling budget or officer or proper strategy.  The well-intentioned words in the plans ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e not translated to proper schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and these are not progressed through the slow, complicated and restrictive CLC system.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The optimum delivery body would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transparent – it is very difficult to find anything out in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Different areas/ schemes would have named officers attached to them who could follow projects through.  A transport body is needed for individual areas that is allowed to develop and w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ork through a vision with a proper budget, proper input from people concerned to bring about a sense of place and safer, people-friendly places, rather than traffic engineers interested </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">primarily </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in traffic flow and increasing traffic volume.  We must work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> towards different priorities in 2014.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no evidence that anyone is working to implement the outlines of LTP3.  L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal bodies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">such as the CLC committees </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">do not have the capacity to assess, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prioritise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and deliver local transport schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3) What is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I am not aware of the working together of borough or district councils across boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at the moment.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  There is a lot of competitio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n for money between areas and schemes and for planning and delivery to work the approval of such schemes needs to be with a higher body that has an overall vision for the whole area.  Transport planning seems to be taken away from any groups that wish to p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">romote sustainable travel throughout the county</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and devolved to county local committees that are just fighting their own little corners and not aware of the need to produce a cohesive network of safe, people-friendly streets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  We have a lot of issues in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with the danger on the A27 to pedestrians.  Many people have been killed on the road which cuts through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> urban areas.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Noone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is willing to look into reducing the speed – as has been done outside </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Worthing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Arundel (40mph).  We still </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have 70mph and we are planning yet more houses on brownfield sites on the other side of the A27 to the main urban area.  The Highways Agency do not want to hear from people who ask for the speed to be reduced.  Who is the Highways Agency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accountable to? Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is is a body that operates across local authority boundaries and yet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it seems very difficult to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hold it accountable for its decisions.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Government departments and national transport agencies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We know that there are meetings between agencies but we have little evidence of changes coming about.  We have asked for the speed on the A27 which effectively cuts through residential areas in the city to be reduced.  There is little evidence that peopl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e’s wishes are taken into account or any changes carried through despite the large number of deaths on this road.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Noone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> seems to know who the Highways Agency is accountable to and thus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">noone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> knows who to influence or how this change can be brought about.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We know that the district and county councils work together to produce plans.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> District Council is having to plan for a large number of extra houses and so they work with WSCC planners to work out how the roads should be improved.  They produce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hugely detailed plans to show how each roundabout on the A27 should be improved and updated to keep the traffic flowing.  However the plans only contain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arrows of connectivity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to show where the new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cyclepaths</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should go in.  They do not show any new cycle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> paths or cy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cle infrastructure at all.  The councils</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> work together well on things they prioritize, but things that are less important to them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cycle paths are only mentioned vaguely and no proper detail is given to carry out any real changes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5) Do the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">current funding streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities? How do current funding streams compare with previous arrangements?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WSCC has had to make huge numbers of cuts and this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reason </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is given for the lack of schemes bei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng brought forward for our roads and for sustainable travel too.  As the roads </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">deteriorate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> over the past few winters, WSCC is fighting a losing battle, with more and more complaints being brought by motorists.  The motorists lobby is obviously very s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">trong so sustainable travel schemes are not prioritized.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Horsham won some LSTF funding – however all the other towns and cities in the county got no money at all.  The funding will not allow a proper job to be done on one of our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gyratories</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– instead cyclists are offered some more shared pavements, and the chance to use 3 toucan crossings to get round a gyratory.  This scheme is being rushed through so that the deadline for spending is not missed and the end result will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">produce that visio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n of proper, safe, segregated paths as in Holland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – but it is a sad compromise just offering those people who are scared of cycling round a busy gyratory the chance to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wait at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 3 toucan crossings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Most cyclists will still use the road as being far quicker a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd then they will be shouted at for not being on the cycle path.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The source of danger for cyclists on the junction will not be removed.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The whole area will not be revamped as a people-friendly instead of a traffic dominated place. For proper local transp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ort planning proper funding must be provided instead of a few drops</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> here and there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  The County cannot plan properly for cycling as it does not put any monies aside for this,  if it is using S106 monies, it has conflicting pulls on this from lots of other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">interest groups, funding from central government has to be bid for and does not get spread evenly around areas.  Apparently there was a fund earlier in 2013 called Cycling Ambition Fund, which seems to have passed us by.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is all piecemeal funding whic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h does not produce satisfactory results for anyone.  So much time is spent on deciding how to deploy scarce resources and the council says it has to save £140 million so there is not much likelihood of proper planning and proper improvements to roads, or a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ny expenditure on the sustainable infrastructure we so badly need.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Sustainable infrastructure will only be put in when it can bid for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> S106 monies when enough houses have been built by new developers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> So if we don’t build more houses, we won’t get any cycling infrastructure!</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6) What impact will the devolution in 2015 of funding to Local Transport Bodies and the introduction of the Single Local Growth Fund have?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I have not heard of this so cannot comme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nt.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> My concern with any procedures that are set up is that inevitably </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, who are politicians, want to do “popular” things as they want to be re-elected.  Therefore if decisions are left entirely to elected representatives to decide how money is s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pent, only certain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">political </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">viewpoints would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">favour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> money being spent on proper cycle infrastructure.  There is no doubt that everyone in our different layers of council knows that they need to tick the boxes about sustainable travel, but when it comes to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> how the money is spent, it is considered more important to please the motorist and to increase traffic flow and capacity.  To get a body to actually put proper cycling infrastructure on the list for funding you either have to change the view of the vocal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">majority or use some of the opinions of the sustainability forums and committees these councils </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">undoubtedly have.  There is a lot of support for cycle infrastructure as most people you speak to would like to cycle safely around our small city, it is just t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hat we need to prove this to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (via petitions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) as otherwise nothing will get done, whatever body or funding structure is introduced.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We fear that the Single Local Growth Fund </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will wipe out any consideration of sustainable transport sche</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mes both big and small.   That is because it is designed to promote jobs supported by road building.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7) How can local authorities attract greater investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? Wha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">t scope is there for the use of alternative funding streams?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local authorities have the responsibility of funding transport infrastructure and so it is unlikely that private investors will volunteer for this.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I have heard that individual streets have been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> asked to finance their own 20mph signs which I think is wrong.  In such cases only richer people who can afford such luxuries could finance such safety measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s for their streets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The children of the poorer families would not be able to pay for their sig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ns, although it is well known that there are more collisions in poorer areas.  For this reason, I do not believe that such things should be outsourced from the state.  I believe that the Highways Authorities bear responsibility for maintaining the roads, s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">etting speed limits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and they should be adequately financed by central government to allow this happen.  At the moment local councils are put under such pressure, that they are barely able to fulfil their statutory obligations, so looking into changing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">speed limits to ensure the safety of pedestrians and cyclists falls to the lottery of S106 funding and the perseverance of local campaigners.  The local council does not have enough money available to put into funding any cycling related infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– although it should do so, to enable people to travel in safety around the area, and to encourage more sustainable travel for health and environmental reasons.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How clear are the lines of accountability for local decision making on transport expen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">diture?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are no lines of accountability.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The impression the average person on the street has is that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WSCC and CDC write whatever they like in their plans, and do whatever they like without paying heed to the views of the ordinary citizen.  Consultati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ons are carried out but the voices of the normal residents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">often appear to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">blatantly ignored</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> - some people have even claimed that the comments to the consultations are not even read</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The councils exert their decision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">making without there being to our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> k</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nowledge any means of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">questioning decisions or bringing anyone to account for their decisions.  The councillors exert unrestrained influence over all decisions and all policy documents and all expenditure. There is no means of redress for any individual or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> group except the ballot box.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  If there are, unknown to us</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, lines of accountability for lo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cal decision making, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have yet to discover them after 4 years of continual campaigning in this city.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>